1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:27,000
 Very nice to be joining such a wonderful gathering of scholars as far away here as the Pacific coast of the United States. I really appreciate the invitation to join you all today and apologize for any internet problems I might have. I am speaking from my office, which is in a rural area of Washington State near Seattle, Washington. And I do hope that my internet will hold up here.

2
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:54,000
 I have really enjoyed what I have been able to watch this morning. The conference started at two o'clock in the morning, my time here. So I was not able to see everything, watch all the presentations, but I have seen some of the most recent ones. And it is wonderful to be able to reflect on the great schism, nearly a thousand years or a millennium into its history, its bad

3
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:22,000
 And tragic history. And I would like to start by commenting as an Orthodox Christian priest, what a tragedy the schism is. And I think we can all agree that the schism of 1054 that in 2054 will be commemorating 30 years from now is a very tragic episode in the history of Christianity.

4
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:44,000
 But also in the history of Western culture. And I would like to speak today about Western culture, about the place of the schism in Western culture, especially a culture that in past years and even centuries has begun to disintegrate and markedly.

5
00:01:44,000 --> 00:02:02,000
 Some of the presentations I've seen this morning have already brought attention to different aspects of that disintegration, that process. But as I say, this tragedy is something we can learn from something that we can even perhaps be inspired to reverse.

6
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:20,000
 And so I want to start by quoting a Orthodox theologian, well known, arguably the most important Orthodox theologian of the 20th century. And that is George Florovsky. He wrote many works, including works of history.

7
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:40,000
 And he used a phrase to characterize the course of history, a history which is so often fraught with tragedy. He said, yes, history is a tragedy whereby we witness the loss of good things in our civilization and culture.

8
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:47,000
 But we as Christians must always remember that history is a creative tragedy.

9
00:02:47,000 --> 00:03:04,000
 It's a creative tragedy. And so in the books that I've written, a four part series of books on the history of the rise and fall of what the West once was, whose overall title is Paradise and Utopia.

10
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:25,000
 I've quoted Florovsky and I've tried to show that this process of history that in many ways is determined by or flows out of the great schism that we can date to 1054, although everyone here, I think, realizes that 1054 itself is something of a phantom date.

11
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:41,000
 And there's there's there's there's much more going on than just that one act of excommunication in Constantinople between Rome and and the ecumenical patriarch that the history that flows out of that event is indeed tragic, but it is also creative.

12
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:56,000
 And and and I would like to think that as we approach the millennium of that fateful day and 1054, July 16th, 1054, what might sadly be called excommunication day.

13
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:09,000
 I don't like the thought of that on the Christian calendar, but that's probably what we can call it for now, that we can look at it as Christians, both from the East and the West in a creative way.

14
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:12,000
 And so what does that mean?

15
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:25,000
 And for me, what that means is going back to the deep past, understanding where we are today by looking into that deep past of the first millennium.

16
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:44,000
 So many people who comment from a Christian point of view on the disintegration of Western culture today, the cultural crisis we live in and here living near Seattle, Washington, I can certainly attest that all around are is evidence of this cultural crisis.

17
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:51,000
 I can talk about all sorts of events that have happened recently in my own neighborhood here, as it were.

18
00:04:51,000 --> 00:05:11,000
 If we look back, we can see and many Christian commentators have done so many historians from a Christian point of view have done so various movements or events that have set the history of the West away from its its Christian origins.

19
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:29,000
 Some of these commentators would point to the sexual revolution, so-called, that began to take a hold in the 1950s and then exploded in the 1960s and then kind of played itself out in the 1970s.

20
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:41,000
 The whole generation whereby, in a revolutionary way, the sexual values of the West simply were altered radically in a non-Christian way.

21
00:05:41,000 --> 00:06:04,000
 And we certainly see the evidence of that today, not only in various movements to normalize the sexual revolution, but even culminating, as has been observed, in the transgender phenomenon, where the biology, biological sex of a human being is itself called into question.

22
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:12,000
 Other cultural commentators would go further back in history to something like this so-called enlightenment.

23
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:14,000
 I don't like that term as a Christian.

24
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:25,000
 I think that the term enlightenment belongs to a Christian sharing of the light of the gospel of Jesus Christ with the world and not its rejection.

25
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:26,000
 And certainly it was rejected.

26
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:34,000
 The gospel was rejected and displaced by the secular culture of the 18th century.

27
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:47,000
 Enlightenment beginning in the 17th century and then playing itself out in the 19th century in movements like Romanticism, which I think is a fascinating movement in the secularization of the West.

28
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:56,000
 But the so-called enlightenment would be seen as a second key turning point in the history of this disintegration.

29
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:09,000
 Other cultural commentators would go even further back in time to the Protestant Reformation, which, of course, affected the West, not really the East immediately and directly.

30
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:10,000
 That is to say, Eastern Christendom.

31
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:22,000
 But the West, Western Christendom, of course, was transformed by the effects of the Protestant Reformation of the 16th and 17th centuries.

32
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:29,000
 And many would say that really is what's responsible for setting things in motion for where we are today.

33
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:52,000
 In fact, it's even been suggested that a fourth turning point in the history of the West can be seen in the rise of what's called nominalism, a kind of scholastic or post-scholastic intellectual movement of theology in the Roman Catholic Church that arose in the 14th century and played itself out in the 15th century.

34
00:07:52,000 --> 00:08:02,000
 Those are four options, and all four do, in fact, explain where we are today in a Christian culture that is in disintegration.

35
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:21,000
 However, I would say, and I think today as we talk about AD 1054 and AD 2054, look forward to it, I would say that we ought to give serious consideration to another turning point.

36
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:26,000
 In fact, the one that I think is most important, and that is indeed the Great Schism.

37
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:38,000
 And what I would like to do is consider the historical disintegration of Western Christian culture from the point of view of the first millennium, the first millennium.

38
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:41,000
 Very few historians have tried to do this.

39
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:51,000
 Almost all historians who talk about the history of the West do so from a second millennium Western perspective.

40
00:08:51,000 --> 00:09:05,000
 And as an Orthodox Christian, I would like to see it from a first millennium Eastern perspective, the history of the West from an Eastern perspective, and one that brings attention to how things were in the first millennium.

41
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:34,000
 And so in the little time that's still left to me, I would just like to bring attention to a few examples of how we can see the first millennium culture grounded in an authentic Christianity that united both the East and the West, a Christianity to which both the Orthodox Church today and the Roman Catholic Church today looks back with love and with respect.

42
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:39,000
 Even Protestant Christians in many cases do so as well.

43
00:09:39,000 --> 00:10:08,000
 To do that, I would like to bring attention to what was a phenomenon in the first millennium, and that is that the West was very influenced by what we would call today the East, the Latin Christendom in Italy and Western Europe and in England and places like this was influenced by the Greek Christianity of that time,

44
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:13,000
 which was part of the West, part of Christendom as a whole.

45
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:32,000
 And if we do this, and if we do this, we see that there was especially found in the East, but also documented in the West as well, an understanding of the human condition that was very positive, very affirmative, and very joyful.

46
00:10:32,000 --> 00:11:01,000
 And I think it's the loss of this affirmative, this optimism about the human condition that was lost in the West as a result of the Great Schism over time, and it's the loss of this affirmative or optimistic theological anthropology that we can bring our attention to and see how progressively it was subverted.

47
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:12,000
 And that subversion of it resulted in some of the problems, perhaps a lot of the problems that arose in the course of the second millennium.

48
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:24,000
 So to do that, let me take us back to that first millennium and to a very important Greek father of the early church, United East and West.

49
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:31,000
 This is Maximos, the confessor, a seventh century father who had his origins in the East.

50
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:35,000
 He was affiliated with St. Saffronios of Jerusalem.

51
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:49,000
 St. Saffronios wrote, by the way, composed a beautiful service of the blessing of water at Theophany, known in the West as Epiphany, on January 6th of every year,

52
00:11:49,000 --> 00:12:02,000
 where the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized was blessed in a ceremonial and even sacramental way with the order that St. Saffronios introduced.

53
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:11,000
 It celebrated the transformation of the world through the presence, the incarnational presence of God in this world.

54
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:18,000
 But Maximos, learning from Saffronios, made his way all around Christendom, East and West.

55
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:25,000
 He had a foot, as it were, in the in the Greek East and a foot, as it were, in the Latin West.

56
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:38,000
 In the latter case, he actually contributed to the formation organization of the Lateran Council of 649, 649, the Lateran Council,

57
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:47,000
 which was an early effort to combat and fight a Eastern Greek, you might call it, heresy called monothelitism,

58
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:55,000
 which subverted the doctrines that that traditional Christianity held about the person of Christ.

59
00:12:55,000 --> 00:13:02,000
 And by subverting the doctrine of the person of Christ subverted our doctrine about man as well.

60
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:06,000
 The man, the humanity that Christ took on himself.

61
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:21,000
 Maximus did a lot of heroic things and ended his life as a confessor, having his tongue cut out and his right hand chopped off because he taught orthodoxy.

62
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:29,000
 That is to say, orthodoxy recognized East and West, both in the Roman Catholic and the Orthodox Church today.

63
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:44,000
 He taught doctrinal integrity in the in the face of resistance by the Byzantine emperors and those theologians they had assembled around them to advance this heresy of monothelitism.

64
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:53,000
 Well, what's what Maximo said about the human condition was quite beautiful and is centered upon the doctrine known as deification.

65
00:13:53,000 --> 00:14:05,000
 Let me read here an example, a short statement by a theologian Maximus, who's very hard to quote, very hard even to read and understand.

66
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:18,000
 He's a very complicated writer, but this quote perhaps gives us a sense of how he presented the ancient doctrine of the deification of the human being in Christ.

67
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:31,000
 Because of the incarnation and through the sacramental life of the church, the human being is elevated to a status of grit of great indescribable beauty.

68
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:33,000
 And this is what he wrote.

69
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:39,000
 A man is the image of God and he becomes God by deification.

70
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:42,000
 He becomes God by deification.

71
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:51,000
 That's a very bold thing for Maximus to say, but it was said as a result of the incarnation and the doctrine as it took hold in the early church.

72
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:52,000
 Maximus continues.

73
00:14:52,000 --> 00:15:08,000
 He rejoices to the full abandoning of all that is in is his by nature because the grace of the spirit triumphs in him and because manifestly God alone is acting in him.

74
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:26,000
 Thus, God and those worthy of God possess in all things one and the same energy, or rather, this common energy is the energy of God alone, since he communicates himself wholly to those who are wholly worthy.

75
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:31,000
 This is Maximus the confessor speaking about deification.

76
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:45,000
 Now, deification as a doctrine was much more prominent in the Greek East than in the Latin West, but it was also found in the Latin West, especially under the influence of the East.

77
00:15:45,000 --> 00:16:06,000
 And there was a time during that first millennium when the West was Eastern, when the West was Eastern during about two centuries, for instance, the popes were from places like the Greek East or Syria or Palestine.

78
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:19,000
 People like Pope Gregory the Great, recognized both as Orthodox and Roman Catholic as a saint.

79
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:30,000
 He spent his time in Constantinople in his early years studying the Byzantine Divine Liturgy and participating in the Greek East.

80
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:41,000
 There are many examples of this, of the sharing of liturgical and sacramental life that came from Constantinople to Rome and parts of the West.

81
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:57,000
 So Maximus and his doctrine of deification built right into that Western Council, the Lateran Council in Rome itself in 649, which he helped organize, was to be found in the West.

82
00:16:57,000 --> 00:17:15,000
 However, the Great Schism, and here we can come to the Great Schism, the Great Schism severed the union between East and West and the influence of that Greek East in its place in Western Christendom and culture.

83
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:26,000
 So that we can find a couple of centuries after the schism, a growing departure from this glorified vision of the human being.

84
00:17:26,000 --> 00:17:30,000
 In the case, for instance, of Pope Innocent III.

85
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:43,000
 Pope Innocent III ruled around the year 1200, and he wrote a document, a treatise, just before he became Pope, called "On the Misery of the Human Condition."

86
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:49,000
 It was called "On Contempt for the World," a subtitle, "On the Misery of the Human Condition."

87
00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:54,000
 This is what Pope Innocent III wrote in his treatise before becoming Pope.

88
00:17:54,000 --> 00:18:08,000
 And of course, as Pope, he ruled in a very influential way in a process known as the Reformation of the Church, of the Roman Catholic Church, this long before the Protestant Reformation.

89
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:19,000
 This is what Pope Innocent III wrote: "Man has been formed of dust, clay, ashes, and a thing more vile, of filthy sperm.

90
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:27,000
 Man has been conceived in the desire of the flesh, in the heat of sensual lust, in the foul stench of wantonness.

91
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:34,000
 He was born to labor, to fear, to suffer, and, most miserable of all, to death.

92
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:39,000
 His evil doings offend God, offend his neighbor, offend himself.

93
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:46,000
 He defiles his good name, contaminates his person, violates his conscience through his shameful acts.

94
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:53,000
 His vanity prompts him to neglect what is most important, most necessary, and most useful.

95
00:18:53,000 --> 00:19:05,000
 Accordingly, he is destined to become the fuel of the everlasting, eternally painful hellfire, the food of voracious, consuming worms.

96
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:14,000
 His destiny is to be a putrid mass that eternally emits a most horrible stench."

97
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:29,000
 Well, this is quite a statement, and I don't think we should see it as a one-off, a kind of exception, to that earlier and glorified anthropology that Maximos witnessed to.

98
00:19:29,000 --> 00:19:41,000
 As a matter of fact, the Misery of the Human Condition, the treatise by Pope Innocent III, what I've just quoted, became something of a so-called medieval bestseller.

99
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:56,000
 It was widely copied and distributed throughout the West, partly because, of course, Pope Innocent III was such an influential figure in the Reformation of the Roman Catholic Church during this time.

100
00:19:56,000 --> 00:20:15,000
 As a result of this new anthropology, this pessimistic anthropology, this very negative anthropology, which this is just a glimpse of, we see that in the West, after the Great Schism and the loss of contact with this earlier first millennium anthropology,

101
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:30,000
 we see the rise and expansion of images, especially of images and treatises that denigrate the human condition and bring attention to its misery.

102
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:37,000
 I will, if I may, I hope I can do this, share here my screen with everyone.

103
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:40,000
 But I'm not sure I'm going to be able to pull this off.

104
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:41,000
 Let's see.

105
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:42,000
 Yes, I can do that.

106
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:44,000
 This is the creation of Adam.

107
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:55,000
 And it shows, but it was done by Greek Byzantine iconographers brought from the Greek East to the Latin West.

108
00:20:55,000 --> 00:21:03,000
 And it shows Christ here on the left-hand side, creating Adam here naked in paradise.

109
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:06,000
 What I want to bring attention to are the faces.

110
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:08,000
 You see, the faces are the same.

111
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:19,000
 It's a really beautiful expression, visual expression, iconographical expression of the doctrine at the heart of this deification we just heard Maximo speak of,

112
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:22,000
 that man is the image of God, image of God.

113
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:30,000
 And so Christ, the Logos, who's the creator of the cosmos, the son of God, creates Adam in his own image.

114
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:33,000
 And you can see this represented in the faces here.

115
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:42,000
 But if we move forward beyond this to the period, the so-called period of the Middle Ages, after the Great Schism,

116
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:48,000
 and under the influence of writers like Innocent the Third, we come across images like this.

117
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:51,000
 So this is the dance of death, I think now you can see it.

118
00:21:51,000 --> 00:22:07,000
 I want to contrast this with if you've ever seen the interior of the famous Church of St. Apollinaire Nuovo in Ravenna, Italy, built under Justinian in the sixth century, also in Italy.

119
00:22:07,000 --> 00:22:18,000
 You'll see a line of saints on either side of the basilica, oriented toward the altar as they move in procession, as it were, toward the kingdom of heaven.

120
00:22:18,000 --> 00:22:25,000
 Humanity deified through communion with God, sacramentally within the liturgical life of the Church.

121
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:28,000
 Well, here, the procession is away from the altar.

122
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:34,000
 You can't really tell with the image, but this is a westward, not an eastward movement.

123
00:22:34,000 --> 00:22:37,000
 It's a, you might say, disorientation.

124
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:46,000
 If orientation means facing east, and it does, of course, this is a disorientation away from the east, which the altar would be over here.

125
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:51,000
 This is the side of the church here, the side of the interior of the church here.

126
00:22:51,000 --> 00:22:55,000
 It's called the dance of death, and it's a reflection on death.

127
00:22:55,000 --> 00:23:06,000
 And if I can show you just a, here's a blow up of it, you can see everyone being led by these skeletal figures to their death.

128
00:23:06,000 --> 00:23:17,000
 And now this, of course, is a perfectly legitimate image, reminding people of their mortality, something that Pope Innocent had so wanted to do.

129
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:32,000
 But what's interesting is the reflection now is no longer on the glory of man's communion with God in the liturgical temple, but on the misery of the human condition and on death.

130
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:41,000
 So what happens in this period after the Great Schism is a growing pessimism about the human condition.

131
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:52,000
 That pessimism in a culture like Christendom, Western Christendom, could not sustain itself very long because Christianity, after all, is anything but pessimistic.

132
00:23:52,000 --> 00:24:01,000
 It's about the transformation of the human being in Christ and the glorification of the human condition in that state.

133
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:07,000
 And so we get the Renaissance as a reaction against this pessimism.

134
00:24:07,000 --> 00:24:12,000
 And we can look at the Renaissance as an alternative view of man's condition.

135
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:22,000
 Here, I hope you can see now the creation of Adam represented by the famous Michelangelo in the Sistine Chapel of Rome.

136
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:30,000
 Here, a Zeus-like God, Michelangelo now represents God as an old man with a gray beard.

137
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:34,000
 Never before really was God represented as Father.

138
00:24:34,000 --> 00:24:37,000
 He was only represented as the incarnate Christ.

139
00:24:37,000 --> 00:24:39,000
 God had no human form.

140
00:24:39,000 --> 00:24:43,000
 The Father had no human form and was not iconographically represented that way.

141
00:24:43,000 --> 00:24:55,000
 And with his barrel chest very much modeled on the Zeus of pagan mythology and iconography, he touches the hand of a limp Adam, who himself looks very physical.

142
00:24:55,000 --> 00:25:09,000
 And the emphasis is now on the physical and natural beauty of the human being rather than the spiritual beauty of the human being in the Renaissance and what follows during the course of the so-called enlightenment.

143
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:21,000
 And so, if I may, I will return to my pictures here to show you some of those images.

144
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:23,000
 Here's an image of the Virgin Mary.

145
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:26,000
 This is Raphael's Madonna of the Pinks.

146
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:31,000
 You see a glorified humanity here in Jesus and also in the Virgin Mary.

147
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:38,000
 But it's a humanity without any reference really whatsoever to the doctrine of deification or the incarnation.

148
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:40,000
 Of course, this is the incarnation.

149
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:44,000
 We know that this is Jesus just born of the Virgin, who is right here.

150
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:47,000
 But nowhere in the icon are we told that this is what's going on.

151
00:25:47,000 --> 00:26:08,000
 Really, it's just a reflection on the beauty of a young woman and her baby lost in their own moment together rather than liturgically rendered as an icon before which a Christian would come into the temple and pray and through prayer and sacramental communion achieve deification.

152
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:13,000
 Now, Jesus is represented in a naked form to celebrate his natural beauty.

153
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:17,000
 But with his nakedness, he becomes impossible to pray to.

154
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:35,000
 And this image by Raphael, the Madonna of the Pinks from the Renaissance, is a good example of the rebellion against that negative pessimistic anthropology articulated by Innocent III and represented in images like the dance of death.

155
00:26:35,000 --> 00:26:38,000
 If we continue with this history.

156
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:43,000
 If we continue with this history, and I know I'm out of time or running out of time quickly here, and I want to honor that.

157
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:52,000
 If we continue in the history of the West, we eventually move from the Madonna or the Virgin to Venus.

158
00:26:52,000 --> 00:27:07,000
 By the 18th century, painters like this, this is the French painter Boucher, begin painting a female beauty no longer as the Virgin Mary, but as the Greek goddess Venus to celebrate the physical beauty of the human being.

159
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:24,000
 In this rebellion against Christian anthropology, which to them seemed in its medieval form after the Great Schism, so negative, they go much further in a non-Christian tradition now and abandon Christianity and its imagery altogether.

160
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:51,000
 And if I may, I will end things here with this 20th century image, which in the wake of Nietzsche and other nihilistic expressions of a rebellion against Christianity altogether and even the optimistic and utopian and secular humanity celebrated in the Renaissance and especially in the Enlightenment.

161
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:54,000
 And now you have the total disintegration of the human being.

162
00:27:54,000 --> 00:27:59,000
 This is Picasso's woman weeping, woman weeping.

163
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:20,000
 And here you see the actual disintegration of the human form altogether in a 20th century that brought forth communism, Nazism, and secular progressivism, and which brings us up to the current moment when we don't know as a culture any longer.

164
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:27,000
 Whether the human being is worthy at all or even in many cases what a human being is.

165
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:30,000
 And I will, I think, end things here.

166
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:32,000
 I could give a few more quotes.

167
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:39,000
 I had some Nietzsche to quote to you, but I think I'd better let that go because I see time has gone away from me here.

168
00:28:39,000 --> 00:28:40,000
 And so I will leave it there.

169
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:42,000
 And so I will leave it there.

170
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:51,000
 But with one final reminder of what George Florovsky said in the 20th century, having witnessed this whole history in his own way.

171
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:58,000
 He said, history may be a tragedy, but for a Christian, it's always a creative tragedy.

172
00:28:58,000 --> 00:29:14,000
 And I do hope that as we move forward toward 2054 to commemorate, sadly, the great schism after one full millennium, we can recover some of that deep past from the first millennium before there was a great schism.

173
00:29:14,000 --> 00:29:16,000
 Hvala što pratite kanal.

